b"[![](../../cdshop/cdinfo.jpg)](../../cdshop/index.htm)  \n[Sacred Texts](../../index.htm)  [Hinduism](../index.htm)  [Index](index.htm)\n[Previous](sbe07015.htm)  [Next](sbe07017.htm)\n\n* * *\n\np. 60\n\n# XIV.\n\n1\\. Now follows the (rule regarding the ordeal by) sacred libation.\n\n2\\. Having invoked terrible deities (such as Durga, the \xc3\x82dityas or others, the\ndefendant) must drink three handfuls of water in which (images of) those\ndeities have been bathed,\n\n[XIII. 3, 5-7. Y. II, 110, 111.\n\nXIV. 2, 4, 5. Y. II, 112, 113.]\n\np. 61\n\n3\\. Uttering at the same time the words, 'I have not done this,' with his face\nturned towards the deity (in question).\n\n4\\. He to whom (any calamity) happens within a fortnight or three weeks (such\nas an illness, or fire, or the death of a relative, or a heavy visitation by\nthe king),\n\n5\\. Should be known to be guilty; otherwise (if nothing adverse happens to\nhim), he is freed from the charge. A just king should honour (with presents of\nclothes, ornaments, &c.) one who has cleared himself from guilt by an ordeal.\n\n* * *\n\n[Next: XV.](sbe07017.htm)\n\n"